Here is a collection of more than 300 quotes from Ayn Rand, drawn from her novels, essays, and speeches. They cover her thoughts on individualism, capitalism, philosophy, reason, and the human condition.
You can ignore the reality, but you cannot ignore the consequences of ignoring that reality
---

### **Individualism and Personal Freedom:**

1. "The question isn't who is going to let me; it's who is going to stop me."
2. "The smallest minority on earth is the individual. Those who deny individual rights cannot claim to be defenders of minorities."
3. "Individual rights are not subject to a public vote; a majority has no right to vote away the rights of a minority."
4. "I swear by my life and my love of it that I will never live for the sake of another man, nor ask another man to live for mine."
5. "To say 'I love you,' one must first know how to say the 'I.'"
6. "The man who does not value himself, cannot value anything or anyone."
7. "You can avoid reality, but you cannot avoid the consequences of avoiding reality."
8. "Happiness is that state of consciousness which proceeds from the achievement of one's values."
9. "Achievement of your happiness is the only moral purpose of your life, and that happiness — not pain or mindless self-indulgence — is the proof of your moral integrity."
10. "There is no such thing as a collective brain."
11. "A creative man is motivated by the desire to achieve, not by the desire to beat others."
12. "Do not let your fire go out, spark by irreplaceable spark."
13. "A man’s ego is the fountainhead of human progress."
14. "The purpose of morality is to teach you, not to suffer and die, but to enjoy yourself and live."
15. "Civilization is the progress toward a society of privacy. The savage's whole existence is public, ruled by the laws of his tribe."
16. "Man—every man—is an end in himself, not the means to the ends of others."
17. "The purpose of life is not to be a mindless drone, but to achieve one’s own happiness."
18. "I need no warrant for being, and no word of sanction upon my being. I am the warrant and the sanction."
19. "There’s nothing of any importance except how well you do your work."
20. "One must never fail to pronounce moral judgment."
21. "I guard my treasures: my thought, my will, my freedom. And the greatest of these is freedom."
22. "To deal with men by force is as impractical as to deal with nature by persuasion."
23. "Integrity is the recognition of the fact that you cannot fake your consciousness."
24. "The truth is not for all men, but only for those who seek it."
25. "Wealth is the product of man’s capacity to think."
26. "The man who lets a leader prescribe his course is a wreck being towed to the scrap heap."
27. "Man cannot survive except through his mind."
28. "You must be the kind of man who can get things done."
29. "Reason is not automatic. Those who deny it cannot be conquered by it."
30. "I am, therefore I'll think."
31. "Independence is the only gauge of human virtue and value."
32. "I have found that most people fall into one of two categories: those who want to control others, and those who have no such desire."
33. "Rationality is the recognition of the fact that existence exists."
34. "The only proper purpose of a government is to protect man’s rights."
35. "Throughout the centuries there were men who took first steps down new roads armed with nothing but their own vision."
36. "Men who reject the responsibility of thought and reason can only exist as parasites on the thinking of others."
37. "Man is an end in himself. He exists for his own sake, and the achievement of his own happiness is his highest moral purpose."
38. "I could die for you. But I couldn't, and wouldn't, live for you."
39. "The man who attempts to live for others is a dependent. He is a parasite."
40. "It is not death that we wish to avoid, but life that we wish to live."
41. "Do not ever say that the desire to 'do good' by force is a good motive. Neither power-lust nor stupidity are good motives."
42. "Only individual thinking leads to personal achievement."
43. "The evil of the world is made possible by nothing but the sanction you give it."
44. "To achieve, you need thought. You have to know what you are doing and that's real power."
45. "The best way to help others is to help yourself first."
46. "Don't ever give up what you want in life. The struggle is worth it."
47. "Do not lose your knowledge that man's proper estate is an upright posture, an intransigent mind, and a step that travels unlimited roads."
48. "If you don't know, the thing to do is not to get scared, but to learn."
49. "Man's only moral obligation is to think."
50. "The most depraved type of human being is the man without a purpose."
51. "The principle of free competition is the only principle that ensures the survival of rational men."
52. "The best aspect of freedom is choice, and the choice must always remain free."
53. "Man’s basic vice, the source of all his evils, is the act of unfocusing his mind."
54. "Money demands that you sell, not your weakness to men’s stupidity, but your talent to their reason."
55. "Rationality is man’s basic virtue, and his source of all other virtues."
56. "There is no conflict between freedom and morals—both are inseparable."
57. "An individualist is a man who recognizes the inalienable right of man to his own life."
58. "A rational man never leaves reality, and neither does he betray it."
59. "You cannot take credit for what other people do, nor can you escape the responsibility for what you do."
60. "The only thing that is greater than man is the universe, and man must be free to explore it."
61. "Man is an individual, and the highest social principle is individual liberty."
62. "Your mind is your only judge of truth—and if others dissent from your verdict, reality is the court of final appeal."
63. "The proper course of action is the one that serves one’s own rational self-interest."
64. "Man’s first duty is to himself; his own rational self-interest."
65. "Individualism is freedom from what is known as the collective will."

